1. Framing: Emphasize the paper\'92s principled disaggregation of \'93climate action\'94 as a contribution.
\f0\b0 \
The paper slightly undersells its intervention in the literature on \'93\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
the determinants of support and opposition for climate action.\'94\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0  As is, the heterogeneity in preferences that you find is framed as explaining \'93\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
how individuals develop preferences\'94 regarding \'93support and opposition for climate action.\'94 This is right; we do learn about how individuals develop preferences. But more directly, you offer a solid theory and evidence about which people prefer which kinds of policy based on the distributional dimensions of compensatory policies. The paper makes an important contribution in helping to desegregate what \'93climate action\'94 means in the first place (policy detail that are often conflated or glossed over under the banner of \'93climate action\'94) and how that affects support among different constituencies. It is not just that support is unevenly distributed or that some policies are more popular than others; you show that different policies have different levels of support in predictable ways. This contribution could be more clear in the intro.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
