\f1\b 2. Vulnerability is a continuous variable.
\f0\b0  In this sentence on page 7: \'93We benchmark these communities against those that are neither ecologically threatened nor policy vulnerable, i.e. the general public.\'94 I would change \'93neither\'94 to \'93neither especially\'94 to be clear that it is a relative, not an absolute distinction--of course, everyone is somewhat ecologically venerable. \
In general, you might talk about about degrees of volnerability, rather than discrete types. I know the analysis presents these as discrete groups for clarity, but one could imaging doing a similar analysis where vulnerability is a continuous variable, exploiting within-group variation in vulnerability. If these data allow you to do so, I\'92d be interested to see it. It also may allow you to comment on differences in the results between the US and Indian samples. \
One clear dimension of variation is percent employed in the fossil fuel sector, where the Cross-Pressured samples are much closer to to the General Population sample than the Fossil Fuel Country samples. We need to know to what extent percent fossil fuel employment or ecological vulnerability accounts for the difference. \
\

\f1\b 3. Clarify the importance of fossil fuel communities in politics.
\f0\b0  If the practical import of the paper relates to\'93how governments can build coalitions\'94 then we might need a few sentences beyond the summary of Bachtel and Scheme at the bottom of page 5 about how important these particular communities are to political coalitions. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \'93Coal country\'94 is a bit misleading for the US sample because you actually sample \'93per capita fossil fuel employment,\'94 which may be mostly oil and natural gas. How well we can generalize from coal could be discussed on pgs. 22-23 and the \'93Role of Community Identity\'94 section. For example, it is not obvious that oil and gas feature \'93workforces that have been culturally distinct and intergenerationally dependent on particular modes of employment.\'94 Indeed you, say that \'93that coal production differs from other fossil fuel industries.\'94 To the extent that you can break out results by BEA codes related to mining vs oil refining etc., you may be able to examine the role that variation in industry structure affects responses. \
To the extent that your sample is broader than coal communities and coal workers, the \'93coal country\'94 moniker undersells the paper. Do coal miners represent an important number of votes in India? They don\'92t in the US, but their image has been mobilized as a symbol far more consequential than their votes. Do White suburbanites who think coal is patriotic share policy preferences with coal communities? Would they fall in line if coal miners were to come out in support of a policy, or would they be re-mobilized to oppose climate action (big government) by a different set of images and rhetorical moves? Additionally, how well do coal communities (or the broader fossil fuel communities measured in the US) proxy for other \'91climate losers\'92 that may be more important voter blocks? Any evidence you have that getting these particular voters into a climate policy coalition matters would lend import to the results.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 4. The correlation between coastal communities and partisanship is a potential confound.
\f0\b0  Do coastal fossil fuel communities have different policy preferences because of their ecological vulnerability or does their coastal location affect both vulnerability and policy preferences. \
\

\f1\b 5. Do specific climate concerns predict support for adaptive infrastucure? 
\f0\b0 The possibility that more precisely defined ecological threats would provoke more support for protective infrastructure is a very interesting idea for future research. Maybe you have tried this, but I wonder if you could get any leverage on that question with these data by looking at things like hurricane damage or flooding by zip code.\
Along these lines, you may be planning on spinning Appendix F as a separate paper. If not,  I would bring the large differences between concerned and unconcerned respondents into the text at the bottom of page 19. These findings directly speak to whether perceived threat affects desire to invest in protective infrastructure--it does!. \
\

\f1\b 6. How do we know that coal being \'93more than a provider of jobs\'94 affects policy preferences? 
\f0\b0 You say that identity and material interest are connected, but the \'93Role of Community Identity\'94 section seems to want to say something about \'93identify-related concerns\'94 that is distinct from material interest in good jobs. The interesting statistic then would be the difference in policy support when a policy is framed on economic grounds or identity grounds. As worded, the question leads with \'93harm jobs\'94 and then says \'93will threaten identities\'94--I am skeptical that \'93because it will threaten the identities of coal workers\'94 is doing any work. Not to say identities (I am a coal worker) are not important. Just that I\'92m not clear how we can disentangle them from material interest.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

